et within the aggro radius. In most dungeons they do, but, in a lot of outdoor zones, a kos mob won't really care about how a different species of kos mob is being treated. As you said, &quot;Treah in Growth has a zone wide call for help radius with certain mobs.&quot; I haven't seen this in action myself, but the fact that only certain mobs help him out is what I was getting at.<br><br>Candide Jeetkunedo<br>Grandmaster Swifttail<br>The Tribunal <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#778899><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/ucrouchinglizard.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Crouching Lizard</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Monk</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(7/7/01 6:54:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=291.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.jumpspot.net/eq/crouchinglizard.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Laotzu's Guide to Advanced Pulling</span><hr size=1> I just read this excellent guide (which needs to be incoporated, along with peoples notes, into the guides on the main site).<br><br>I'd like to make an addition to the list if I may:<br><br>Buff Pulling<br><br>If one or more mobs in a group is a caster, they will periodically buff themselves and the other mobs nearby.  Wait until you see &quot;a_mob begins to cast a spell...&quot; and then aggro one of the melee mobs.  If timed right, the one casting the spell will not aggro.  Guess he was too busy buffing ;)  Depending on which mob was casting, this can really help to break up a camp.<br><br><br>Example of buff pulling the King room in Lower Guk:<br><br>What I did was to wait until the Tactitian started casting.  Then I pulled a kinght on the floor.  The 3 frogs on the floor all came after me but the three in the upper tunnel did not aggro.  Reason being the Tactitian (spot) is the key to aggroing those upper mobs.<br><br><br>Also, has anyone else noticed this?   In a group of 2 mobs, if you aggro one by say throwing a knife at him, when they start to walk back, the one you originally attacked leaves FIRST, leaving the one that had aggro passed to him standing there for a second or two before he leaves.  We've all see this happen but I think many monks don't realize that it's predictable which one will hang around longer.  So, if you really want mob A, aggro mob B first.<br><br><br>CL <p><img src="http://jumpspot.net/eq/mendbug.gif"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/uevilnight.showPublicProfile?language=EN>EvilNight</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master</span><br>  Posts: 288<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(8/22/01 7:44:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=291.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Reverse YoYo Pulling.</span><hr size=1> I've been beaten severely about the head and shoulders by a few fellow Monks for not posting my favorite tactic up here so I'm posting it now. This is your bread and butter for Monks between 30 and 60 in group situations. It's related to the Bind Point Splitting in the guide, but different enough to be its own tactic.<br><br>This tactic is a variant of YoYo pulling... it's almost like Reverse YoYo. This tactic is used to split high level MoBs, especially yellows and reds. It works in the old world and Kunark best. It can be used in Velious but only if you've gotten so good at it that it's almost an instinct. Let me explain how the MoBs work to lay this out very simply.<br><br>With any Kunark and Norrathian MoB, there is a delay between the moment you feign death and the moment they walk back to their home point. This is a random delay. Some Velious MoBs exhibit this delay as well but it is far less common, especially in higher level MoBs.<br><br>This delay is the key to the YoYo tactics. With standard YoYo pulling, you pull all MoBs in the camp and feign. Usually, one of them leaves after the others, they rarely all go back at the same time. YoYo pulling is simply popping back up and kicking that last MoB upside the head after his friends have moved back out of aggro range. The Reverse YoYo tactic works backwards, you end up getting the first MoB that returns and not the last.<br><br>The biggest problem with YoYo pulling is that with higher level MoBs after Lvl 32, you don't get memwipes all the time. You pop up and find that the other MoBs who went home are coming at you full speed. This is bad for YoYo, but essential for Reverse YoYo. If you get a successful memwipe, Reverse YoYo will not work.<br><br>Our example is an Orc camp in the Crystal Caverns. We have three Mobs in the camp. All con high blue to red to the pulling Monk. His group is set up at some distance to give him room to work the spawn.<br><br>Our Monk pulls all three Orcs out away from the camp and feigns. After a few moments, one of the Orcs returns to the camp, while the other two stay. The first Orc reaches his home point, turns around, and stops moving. Now that he is home again, you MUST feign death one more time while lying there. I have never seen this second feign fail to completely memwipe that first MoB at his home point.<br><br>Soon after, the other two Orcs start returning home. As soon as they are within aggro range of the first Orc, but BEFORE they themselves reach their home point, our Monk stands up.<br><br>The late returning Orcs are still aggro on the Monk, so they instantly whirl around and come running back. In the process, they re-aggro the first Orc who was sitting happily memwiped at his home point. Our Monk waits for all three Orcs to return to him, and feigns again.<br><br>As soon as he hits the ground, the late arriving Orcs return to their home points. The first Orc however now stays put. He has been newly aggroed, so now he waits out the initial delay. The returning Orcs never lost aggro to begin with, so they start walking back immediately.<br><br>Once they return to their home points, our Monk feigns death once more. They are memwiped (bout a 90% probability). Our Monk pops up, kicks the remaining Orc in the teeth, and brings him back to the group.<br><br>This tactic works miracles, as it tends to work best in places where the more conventional tactics fail. It will take you a lot of practice to get this right.<br><br><br><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>Things to remember.</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br><br>You cannot use this tactic on MoBs that are 32nd level and lower, since FD will ALWAYS memwipe them, and you won't be able to get the return aggro necessary for this to work. The good news is that in that situation, normal YoYo pulling works better anyway.<br><br>If you cannot see the MoBs you are splitting, this is a very tough technique to use. You'll have to master the timing if you cannot see them.<br><br>This technique does not work on wandering MoBs, since they have no home point.<br><br>You must score a memwipe on that first MoB, or you won't get the delay once he comes back to you.<br><br>You must FAIL to memwipe the other MoBs that are returning to camp. They have to reaggro on you when you stand. This can be a bit tough since you will have to feign at least twice without getting a memwipe on them. Against high level MoBs, you'll find they tend to remember you no matter what you do, so this is where it works best.<br><br>If you are high enough level that the MoBs will not pass the hate list, this tactic will not work. Of course, who cares, since you can just go up and hit the one you want and pull him without fear of the others coming as well.<br><br>Having another puller to tag-pull off of you is invaluable. Using the YoYo tactics you can always split the MoBs farther apart, but in some circumstances you may have trouble wiping enough aggro to stop the others from coming after you. If you have a tag puller all you must do is separate them apart a good distance (easily done) and let him tag them off of you.<br><br>If you combine this with YoYo pulling, there is no reason that you can't split the camp with a single pull. If you get a memwpie, use normal YoYo and get the last one. If you don't get a memwipe, use Reverse YoYo to get the first one. Either way you win.<br><br>This tactic wouldn't have been possible without the Feign Death &quot;nerf&quot; we all hated so much. Thanks VI! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>Raviel Darkfyre<BR>53rd Disciple of Quellious<BR><b>Insidious Blood</b></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/uevilnight.showPublicProfile?language=EN>EvilNight</A> at: 8/22/01 7:52:03 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#778899><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/uvodalusthemonk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Vodalus the Monk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Monk</span><br>  Posts: 21<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(8/22/01 9:55:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=291.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Reverse YoYo Pulling.</span><hr size=1> excelent guide, i comend you on your in depth knowledge of feign death pulling.  Many of these techniques i have had work, or use regularly, but was not sure as to why they really worked.<br><br>evil, that usualy does work, because the chance of a non wandering mob to re aggro is much less.  however im pretty confident it is not fool proof.  I cant think of an exact instance, but im pretty sure i h